{"text":"Not sure if the raspberry route would be a good idea. They use Broadcomm chips, and Broadcomm are... well lets say - not the most friendliest towards open source. You will have problems and trouble with drivers for their chips and hardware."},{"text":"
"},{"text":"
"},{"text":"I see lots of Single Board manufacturers use Rockchip. Maybe they could be a better alternative. Or heck if you really want to embrace being open, Risc-V would be the way to go to have the ISA open as well."},{"text":"
"},{"text":"
"},{"text":"Also you will need to figure out a way to get the phone into proper standby, where it still is connected to cellular and can receive data, but burns through way less energy than lets say these Single Board Computer systems use up on idle."},{"text":"
"},{"text":"
"},{"text":"Maybe a secondary mini system with a mini chip that keeps connectivity up on standby?"},{"text":"
"},{"text":"
"},{"text":"Just my 2 cents"}
